PLOT_OUTLINE:\nLogline: A charismatic Indian nationalist, disillusioned by Gandhi\'s pacifism, forges alliances with the Axis powers during World War II, leading a daring but ultimately tragic fight for India\'s independence, forcing him to confront the moral complexities of his choices and the devastating impact on those who followed him.\n\nThree-Act Plot Outline:\n\nAct I: The Fire Within (1897-1939)\nIntroduce Subhash Chandra Bose\'s privileged upbringing and early exposure to British colonial rule. Show his burgeoning nationalist sentiments and his academic success, including his passing of the Indian Civil Service exam, which he ultimately rejects.\nBose joins the Indian National Congress and rises through its ranks, working alongside Mahatma Gandhi and Jawaharlal Nehru. Highlight his more radical views and his belief in complete independence, contrasting with Gandhi\'s approach. Show the growing ideological rift through specific debates and disagreements.\nBose becomes President of the Congress but clashes with Gandhi and other leaders over strategy and ideology. The growing tension leads to his resignation and expulsion from the party. Show the impact of this on his supporters and the growing sense of isolation.\n\nAct II: The Axis Gamble (1940-1943)\nBose, seeking international support for India\'s independence, travels to Europe and forms an alliance with Nazi Germany. He establishes the Free India Centre and recruits Indian prisoners of war to form the Free India Legion. Deepen the moral ambiguity by showing Bose\'s internal conflict, his awareness of the Nazis\' atrocities, and his justifications for the alliance as a means to an end. Show the reactions of his followers, some supportive, some questioning.\nShowcase the complexities of his alliance with the Axis powers, including his meetings with Hitler and the moral compromises he makes. Include scenes that highlight the difficult choices he faces and the compromises he makes.\nRecognizing the shifting tides of the war, Bose travels to Japan, where he receives support to form the Indian National Army (INA). He rallies Indian soldiers and civilians in Southeast Asia, inspiring them with his vision of a free India. Show the INA\'s formation and the diverse backgrounds of the soldiers, highlighting their hopes and dreams.\n\nAct III: The Price of Freedom (1944-1945)\nThe INA, under Bose\'s leadership, fights alongside the Japanese in the Imphal campaign, a pivotal moment in the fight for India\'s independence. Show the brutal realities of war, the sacrifices made by the soldiers, and the impact on the local population.\nThe campaign fails, and the INA suffers heavy losses. The British forces push back, and the dream of a liberated India faces a devastating setback. Show the disillusionment and despair of the INA soldiers and the impact on the civilians who supported them.\nBose, facing defeat, attempts to escape to the Soviet Union but dies in a plane crash. The film concludes with the aftermath of his death, the controversy surrounding his fate, and his enduring legacy as a revolutionary figure. Show the differing opinions on his legacy, the debates about his choices, and the impact on the Indian independence movement.\n\nBOX_OFFICE_REPORT:\nBox Office Potential Report: "Netaji: The Subhash Chandra Bose Story"\n\nExecutive Summary:\n\n"Netaji: The Subhash Chandra Bose Story," based on the provided plot outline, has the potential to be a commercially viable film with strong appeal to both Indian and international audiences, particularly those interested in historical dramas, biopics, and stories of resistance against colonialism. The film\'s success will depend on several factors, including the quality of the filmmaking, the star power of the cast, and the marketing strategy. Comparable films suggest a potential box office range, but the unique subject matter and cultural relevance could elevate the film\'s performance.\n\nComparable Films and Box Office Analysis:\n\